Secured and monitored web infrastructure
========================================

A user wants to access the website www.foobar.com from a browser.

1. The user types https://www.foobar.com in the browser.
2. The browser asks DNS to translate www.foobar.com into an IP address.
3. The DNS zone for foobar.com has a www record that points to the public IP
   address of the HAproxy load balancer.
4. The user's browser opens an HTTPS connection to the load balancer.
5. The load balancer firewall allows only the required public traffic, such as
   HTTPS on port 443.
6. HAproxy uses the SSL certificate for www.foobar.com to decrypt the HTTPS
   request.
7. HAproxy forwards the request to one of the two backend servers.
8. Each backend server has a firewall that only allows required traffic from
   trusted sources, such as traffic from the load balancer.
9. Nginx on the selected backend server receives the request.
10. Nginx serves static content directly or forwards dynamic requests to the
    application server on the same machine.
11. The application server runs the application code from its local application
    files.
12. If data is needed, the application server communicates with MySQL.
13. Write operations go to the Primary MySQL node.
14. Read operations can go to a Replica MySQL node if the application is
    configured to use replicas for reads.
15. Monitoring clients on all three servers collect metrics and logs and send
    them to a monitoring service such as Sumo Logic.
16. The response is sent back through Nginx, then HAproxy, then to the user's
    browser over HTTPS.

Infrastructure
--------------

Load balancer server:

    Components:
        - HAproxy load balancer
        - Firewall
        - SSL certificate for www.foobar.com
        - Monitoring client

Server 1:

    Components:
        - Firewall
        - Nginx web server
        - Application server
        - Application files, which are the website code base
        - MySQL Primary database
        - Monitoring client

Server 2:

    Components:
        - Firewall
        - Nginx web server
        - Application server
        - Application files, which are the website code base
        - MySQL Replica database
        - Monitoring client

Why each additional element is added
------------------------------------

The three firewalls are added to control network access to each server. One
firewall protects the load balancer, and one firewall protects each backend
server.

The SSL certificate is added so www.foobar.com can be served over HTTPS. It
allows the browser to verify the identity of the website and create an encrypted
connection.

The three monitoring clients are added to collect data from every server in the
infrastructure. They send metrics and logs to a monitoring platform, which helps
engineers detect problems and understand system behavior.

What firewalls are for
----------------------

Firewalls filter incoming and outgoing network traffic based on rules.

In this infrastructure, the load balancer firewall should allow public HTTPS
traffic from users and should block unnecessary ports. The backend server
firewalls should only allow required traffic from trusted sources, such as
traffic from HAproxy to Nginx and database replication traffic between MySQL
nodes.

Firewalls reduce the attack surface by preventing direct access to services
that should not be exposed publicly, such as MySQL.

Why traffic is served over HTTPS
--------------------------------

Traffic is served over HTTPS to encrypt communication between the user's
browser and www.foobar.com. This protects sensitive information such as
passwords, session cookies, personal data, and form submissions.

HTTPS also provides authentication because the SSL certificate proves that the
browser is communicating with the real www.foobar.com domain, as long as the
certificate is valid and trusted.

What monitoring is used for
---------------------------

Monitoring is used to observe the health, performance, and availability of the
infrastructure.

It can track CPU usage, memory usage, disk usage, network traffic, HTTP status
codes, response time, Nginx requests, application errors, MySQL performance,
replication delay, and whether each service is running.

Monitoring also helps alert engineers when something is wrong, such as a server
being down, disk space becoming low, high error rates, or database replication
falling behind.

How the monitoring tool collects data
-------------------------------------

A monitoring client, also called an agent or data collector, runs on each
server.

The client collects system metrics from the operating system, reads logs from
services such as Nginx and MySQL, and can collect application metrics if the
application exposes them.

The monitoring client then sends this data to a monitoring service such as Sumo
Logic, Datadog, New Relic, or Prometheus with a remote storage and alerting
system.

Monitoring web server QPS
-------------------------

QPS means queries per second, or how many requests the web server handles each
second.

To monitor Nginx QPS, enable Nginx access logs or the Nginx status module, then
configure the monitoring client to collect Nginx request data. The monitoring
platform can calculate QPS by counting the number of HTTP requests received over
a time interval and dividing by the number of seconds in that interval.

For example, if Nginx receives 3,000 requests in 60 seconds, the QPS is 50.

Issues with this infrastructure
-------------------------------

SSL termination at the load balancer:

    Terminating SSL at the load balancer means HTTPS is decrypted at HAproxy.
    If traffic from HAproxy to the backend servers is sent over plain HTTP, the
    internal network traffic is not encrypted.

    This can be a security issue if an attacker gains access to the internal
    network or can inspect traffic between the load balancer and backend
    servers. A stronger design would re-encrypt traffic between HAproxy and the
    backend servers or use end-to-end HTTPS.

Only one MySQL server accepts writes:

    Having only one MySQL Primary server capable of accepting writes creates a
    write bottleneck and a single point of failure for write operations.

    If the Primary database fails, the application cannot write new data until a
    Replica is promoted or the Primary is restored. This can cause downtime or
    data consistency problems if failover is not automated and tested.

Same components on every backend server:

    Having the database, web server, and application server on the same backend
    machines can be a problem because the components compete for the same CPU,
    memory, disk, and network resources.

    It also makes scaling less flexible. Web traffic, application processing,
    and database load usually grow differently, so each layer should often be
    scaled independently.

    This design also increases the impact of maintenance. Updating or fixing
    one layer on a server can affect the other layers running on the same
    machine.
